## 3️⃣ Minimal Makefile fragment

```make
# -------------------------------------------------
#  Build the OCaml+C++ binding
# -------------------------------------------------
OCAMLFLAGS   = -thread -I +camlp4
CXXFLAGS     = -O2 -Wall -fPIC -I$(shell ocamlc -where) -I/path/to/blocksci/include
LDFLAGS      = -L/path/to/blocksci/lib -lblocksci   # ← link the real BlockSci lib

all: libblocksci_stubs.a libblocksci.cma

# 1. Compile the C++ stub as a position‑independent object
blocksci_stubs.o: blocksci_stubs.cpp
	$(CXX) $(CXXFLAGS) -c $< -o $@

# 2. Archive it (OCaml expects a .a for -custom linking)
libblocksci_stubs.a: blocksci_stubs.o
	ar rcs $@ $^

# 3. Build the OCaml bytecode library (exposes the .mli)
libblocksci.cma: blocksci.cmo
	ocamlc -a $^ -o $@

# 4. Compile the OCaml interface (no implementation needed)
blocksci.cmo: blocksci.mli
	ocamlc -c $<

clean:
	rm -f *.o *.a *.cmo *.cma
```

*Replace* `/path/to/blocksci/include` and `/path/to/blocksci/lib` with the actual locations of your BlockSci headers and library.

### Using the library

```ocaml
(* test.ml --------------------------------------------------- *)
let () =
  Blocksci.iter_blocks (fun blk ->
    Printf.printf "height=%d hash=%s time=%.0f\n"
      (Blocksci.block_height blk)
      (Blocksci.block_hash blk)
      (Blocksci.block_timestamp blk)
  )
```

Compile & run:

```sh
ocamlc -custom -I . -c test.ml
ocamlc -custom -I . test.cmo libblocksci.cma libblocksci_stubs.a -o test \
       -L/path/to/blocksci/lib -lblocksci
./test
```

You now have a **fully functional OCaml binding** that lets OCaml programmers execute arbitrary code on every block in a BlockSci blockchain, with proper memory management and exception handling. Happy hacking!
